ictions of the 1920s, which may be best understood not as the Jazz Age or the Age of Prohibition, but as the Age of the Klan. Ku Klux Kulture gives us an unsettling glimpse into the past, arguing that the Klan did not die so much as melt into America’s prevailing culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPopular culturezUnited Statesy20th century. 0aPopular culture--United States--20th century. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  a1920s.  aKu Klux Klan.  aanti-Catholicism.  aanti-Semitism.  acultural pluralism.  aethnonationalism.  aimagined community.  apopular culture.  awhite supremacism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831107119360 cprintz978022637615840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226376295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226376295/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles